{
  "text": "Negative regulation of CD4 + and CD8 + cell activation is controlled in part by cytotoxic lymphocyte antigen-4:B7 (CTLA-4:B7) (5) and PD-1:PD-L1 interactions [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Both CTLA-4 and PD-1 knockout mice develop systemic autoimmunity, although the phenotypes are qualitatively and quantitatively quite different [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . CTLA-4 plays an important role in the negative regulation of CD4 responses, but its direct role in CD8 + T cell regulation is less clear. CTLA-4 plays little apparent role in regulating responses of naive T cells [CITATION_6] ; however, Gajewski and colleagues have reported evidence that CTLA-4 negatively regulates responses in primed CD8 + T cells [CITATION_7] . PD-1 appears to play an important role in both early decisions related to peripheral CD8 + T cell tolerance [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] and downregulating responses of primed and chronically antigen-stimulated CD8 + T cells [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] . In vitro data suggest that a combined program of costimulatory signals (i.e., lack of CD28 plus PD-1 signaling) results in both the generation and maintenance of CD8 + T cell tolerance [CITATION_12] .",
